#compdef lq
# =============================================================================
# lq — Even Solbraa's (clux) "low overhead yq/tq/jq cli" —
#      a Rust CLI that combines jq-style JSON querying with
#      YAML + JSON + TOML input/output format conversion in
#      one small binary.  Effectively acts as yq + tq + jq
#      simultaneously, with format detection from file
#      extension OR explicit --input flag.  Designed for
#      fast Kubernetes-style YAML manipulation + TOML
#      config-file editing + jq pipelines.
#      Distinguishing from yq (mikefarah/yq, Go), tq
#      (cryptaliagy/tq), jq (canonical), gron, and other
#      structured-data CLIs by:
#        - SINGLE BINARY FOR 3 FORMATS — yq + jq + tq in
#          one tool; choose input via --input or auto-
#          detect from extension; choose output via
#          --output for cross-format conversion
#        - jq WRAPPER ARCHITECTURE — lq delegates the
#          query language to system jq (must be in PATH);
#          lq handles only format conversion + jq orchestration
#        - 3 INPUT FORMATS via --input:
#            * yaml (default for stdin or .yml/.yaml)
#            * json (auto for .json)
#            * toml (auto for .toml)
#        - 3 OUTPUT FORMATS via --output:
#            * jq (default raw jq output)
#            * yaml (--yaml-output shortcut: -y)
#            * toml (--toml-output shortcut: -t)
#        - SHORTCUT FLAGS:
#            * -y / --yaml-output  — equivalent to --output yaml
#            * -t / --toml-output  — equivalent to --output toml
#            * -T / --toml-input   — equivalent to --input toml
#            * -J / --json-input   — equivalent to --input json
#        - IN-PLACE EDITING via -i / --in-place — modify
#          file directly (similar to sed -i); critical for
#          Kubernetes manifest manipulation
#        - SPLIT MODE via -s / --split QUERY — execute a
#          per-document jq query to compute a filename
#          template, then write each document to its own
#          file:
#            lq --split '"./" + (.metadata.name) + "_" +
#                        (.kind | ascii_downcase) + ".yaml"' \
#               . manifests.yaml
#          — splits a multi-document YAML into per-resource
#          files named like `nginx_deployment.yaml`,
#          `nginx_service.yaml`, etc.
#        - JQ PASS-THROUGH FLAGS:
#            * -c / --compact-output  — jq -c
#            * -r / --raw-output      — jq -r
#            * -j / --join-output     — jq -j (no newlines)
#            * -L PATH                — jq -L (module path)
#        - MULTI-DOCUMENT YAML via serde-saphyr — YAML
#          files containing multiple --- separated documents
#          are parsed as a list of documents; each can be
#          queried separately
#        - STRICT DUPLICATE-KEY HANDLING — by default,
#          duplicate keys in YAML cause an error (unlike
#          permissive parsers); ensures correctness for
#          Kubernetes manifests (issue #86 tracks a possible
#          --duplicates=last-wins flag)
#        - SMALL BINARY — ~5MB after LTO + strip; competitive
#          with mikefarah/yq's binary size despite needing
#          system jq
#      Used by: Kubernetes administrators manipulating YAML
#      manifests in CI pipelines, infrastructure engineers
#      converting between YAML / JSON / TOML configs,
#      cargo + crate authors editing Cargo.toml files via
#      jq queries, and as a reference implementation of
#      toml + serde_json + serde_saphyr + clap derive +
#      jq orchestration composition in Rust.
#
# Author:  Even Solbraa (clux on GitHub) — Norwegian Rust
#          developer, lead maintainer of kube-rs (the
#          canonical Rust Kubernetes client).  Released
#          lq ~2024; current version 0.16.0; active
#          development through 2026.  License: Apache-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/clux/lq
#          https://github.com/clux/lq/blob/main/lq.rs
#          https://github.com/clux/lq/blob/main/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     lq.rs (single-file binary) — uses clap v4 derive
#          (well-documented elsewhere).  Headline library:
#          **toml** (the new variant being documented here,
#          opening Axis 25 — TOML Parsing).
# Library: toml (https://github.com/toml-rs/toml —
#          "Rust TOML Parser" — Alex Crichton (alexcrichton
#          on GitHub) + toml-rs working group.  Distinct
#          from all previously-documented Rust libraries
#          by being:
#             1. TOML 1.0 SPEC COMPLIANT — implements the
#                TOML v1.0.0 spec finalized 2021 (and the
#                subsequent 1.1.0-rc1 draft).  TOML is
#                Tom Preston-Werner's "Tom's Obvious,
#                Minimal Language" config format designed
#                for human-readable configuration files.
#             2. SERDE INTEGRATION — toml-rs is a serde
#                serializer + deserializer.  The same
#                #[derive(Serialize, Deserialize)] structs
#                work for JSON / YAML / TOML / RON /
#                MessagePack:
#                   use serde::{Serialize, Deserialize};
#                   #[derive(Serialize, Deserialize)]
#                   struct Cargo {
#                       package: Package,
#                       dependencies: HashMap<String, String>,
#                   }
#                   let cargo: Cargo = toml::from_str(text)?;
#                   let text = toml::to_string(&cargo)?;
#             3. PRESERVE_ORDER FEATURE — opt-in (default
#                off) for preserving key insertion order
#                during round-trip serialization.  Critical
#                for editing Cargo.toml files without
#                scrambling sections.  Used by lq.
#             4. PARSE → toml::Value UNTYPED — alternative
#                to typed structs; toml::Value enum (Table,
#                Array, String, Integer, Float, Boolean,
#                Datetime) for runtime-polymorphic access:
#                   let v: toml::Value = text.parse()?;
#                   if let Some(name) = v["package"]["name"].as_str() { ... }
#             5. DATETIME SUPPORT — TOML's distinctive
#                feature: native first-class datetime
#                values (offset-datetime, local-datetime,
#                local-date, local-time) parsed into
#                toml::value::Datetime (separate from
#                chrono / time crates by design).
#             6. PRETTY-PRINT via toml_edit — companion
#                crate toml_edit (also in toml-rs org)
#                provides AST-preserving round-trip
#                editing for in-place TOML modifications
#                without reformatting unrelated sections
#                (used by cargo-add, cargo-edit, etc.).
#             7. PURE RUST — no Cgo; cross-platform Rust
#                only.  Distinct from toml-c (Tom Preston-
#                Werner's C reference implementation).
#             8. ZERO-COPY where possible — toml-rs borrows
#                from input lifetime for string slices.
#             9. CARGO ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — toml-rs is
#                Cargo's TOML parser; every Rust project's
#                Cargo.toml is parsed by toml-rs.  Bedrock
#                of the Rust packaging ecosystem.
#            10. ALEX-CRICHTON / TOML-RS ECOSYSTEM
#                PROVENANCE — Alex Crichton (alexcrichton)
#                is a Rust core team member, original
#                creator of Cargo (with Carl Lerche), now
#                at Fastly working on wasmtime + Bytecode
#                Alliance.  toml-rs is Alex's TOML library
#                from the early Cargo days, now community-
#                maintained under the toml-rs GitHub
#                organization.  Distinct from David Tolnay
#                (serde / thiserror / anyhow / serde_yaml),
#                Sean McArthur (Hyperium / reqwest / tonic
#                — 2-library author), Sindre Sorhus
#                (Node CLI ecosystem).  Alex Crichton's
#                contributions span Cargo + wasmtime +
#                cap-std + bindgen + toml-rs.)
# License: MIT OR Apache-2.0 (toml); Apache-2.0 (lq)
# Status:  toml — 1,045+ stars on toml-rs/toml, ~700M
#          crates.io downloads (TOP-5 Rust crate by
#          downloads — second only to serde + libc + log).
#          Used by:
#            * cargo (Cargo.toml parser)
#            * rust-analyzer (config parsing)
#            * mdbook (book.toml)
#            * cargo-make, cargo-edit, cargo-add,
#              cargo-binstall, cargo-generate, cargo-cyclonedx,
#              ... (every cargo-* subcommand)
#            * rust-toolchain.toml resolvers
#            * gitoxide / gix (Git in Rust)
#            * cargo-shuttle / cargo-leptos / cargo-dioxus
#            * Helix editor (config)
#            * Zellij (config)
#            * starship (cross-shell prompt config)
#            * sccache (config)
#            * lq (THIS — TOML manipulation CLI)
#            * 200,000+ Rust applications
#          lq — 49+ stars on clux/lq, used by Kubernetes
#          admins + infrastructure engineers.
#
